Fraud Detect

Dataset

For this experiment we are using TalkingData AdTracking Fraud Detection Challenge located on Kaggle

Dataset Details

  • ip: ip address of click.
  • app: app id for marketing.
  • device: device type id of user mobile phone (e.g., iphone 6 plus, iphone 7, huawei mate 7, etc.)
  • os: os version id of user mobile phone
  • channel: channel id of mobile ad publisher
  • click_time: timestamp of click (UTC)
  • attributed_time: if user download the app for after clicking an ad, this is the time of the app download
  • is_attributed: the target that is to be predicted, indicating the app was downloaded

Exploring data

plotting the relationship between attribute_time and is_attributed

df %>% 
  mutate(attributed_time_is_na = ifelse(is.na(attributed_time) , 'YES', 'NO')) %>% 
  group_by(attributed_time_is_na, is_attributed) %>%
  summarise(total = n())  %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(attributed_time_is_na), y = total)) +  geom_bar(stat='identity') + ggtitle('grouping by attributed_time_is_na (No Filter)')
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'attributed_time_is_na' (override with `.groups` argument)

df %>% 
  filter(is_attributed == 1) %>%
  mutate(attributed_time_is_na = ifelse(is.na(attributed_time) , 'YES', 'NO')) %>% 
  group_by(attributed_time_is_na, is_attributed) %>%
  summarise(total = n())  %>%
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(attributed_time_is_na), y = total)) +  geom_bar(stat='identity') + ggtitle('grouping by attributed_time_is_na (Filter: is_attributed == 1)')
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'attributed_time_is_na' (override with `.groups` argument)

as we can see, where we apply filter is_attributed == 1 the NA values tends to be zero this suggests that we can delete this column.

Data Munging

  • removing attributed_time
  • extracting the day of the week and the hour of the column click_time
  • creating the period column with the cut function passing the time as a parameter
  • removing click_time
df <- df %>% 
  select(-c(attributed_time)) %>% 
  mutate(weekday = Weekday(click_time), hour = hour(click_time)) %>% 
  mutate(period = cut(hour, breaks = 4))  %>%
  select(-c(click_time, hour))

make columns categorical

categorical.vars <- c('app', 'device', 'os', 'channel', 'is_attributed', 'weekday', 'ip')

to.factors <- function(df, variables){
  for (variable in variables){
    df[[variable]] <- as.factor(df[[variable]])
  }
  return(df)
}

# apply to.factors function
df <- to.factors(df = df, variables = categorical.vars)

check if the dataset is unbalanced

prop.table(table(df$is_attributed))
## 
##       0       1 
## 0.99773 0.00227

as we can see, the dataset is unbalanced

using SMOTE to balance the dataset

df <- as.data.frame(df)
df <- SMOTE(is_attributed ~. ,df, perc.over = 100,perc.under=200)
prop.table(table(df$is_attributed))
## 
##   0   1 
## 0.5 0.5

splitting data

df[,'index'] <- ifelse(runif(nrow(df)) < 0.8,1,0)
trainset <- df[df$index==1,]
testset <- df[df$index==0,]

trainColNum <- grep('index', names(trainset))
trainset <- trainset[,-trainColNum]
testset <- testset[,-trainColNum]

nrow(trainset)
## [1] 715
nrow(testset)
## [1] 193

training using SVM

model_svm <- svm(is_attributed ~ ., data = trainset, kernel = "linear", cost = 2)

Plotting ROC Curve

pred <- prediction(as.numeric(predict), testset$is_attributed)

plot(perf,colorize=TRUE)
